module.exports = {"data":{"post":{"id":"/home/travis/build/simonagren/simonagren.github.io/content/posts/2018-11-18--part2-azurefunction/index.md absPath of file >>> MarkdownRemark","html":"<p>\n  <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/funcpnp2-55add6717461e76d8487682f8791bdf0-48538.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n  \n  <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n    style=\"position: relative; display: block; ; max-width: 800px; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\"\n  >\n    <span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n      style=\"padding-bottom: 50%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n    >\n      <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        style=\"width: 100%; height: 100%; margin: 0; vertical-align: middle; position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; box-shadow: inset 0px 0px 0px 400px transparent;\"\n        alt=\"pnp and azure func\"\n        title=\"\"\n        src=\"/static/funcpnp2-55add6717461e76d8487682f8791bdf0-48538.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/funcpnp2-55add6717461e76d8487682f8791bdf0-bed0f.png 200w,\n/static/funcpnp2-55add6717461e76d8487682f8791bdf0-5fd34.png 400w,\n/static/funcpnp2-55add6717461e76d8487682f8791bdf0-48538.png 800w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px\"\n      />\n    </span>\n  </span>\n  \n  </a>\n    </p>\n<h1>The posts in this series</h1>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://simonagren.github.io/azurefunction-v2-pnpjs/\" target=\"_blank\">Part 1 - Azure Functions V2 + VS Code + PnPJs === true</a></li>\n<li>Part 2 - Azure Functions V2 + VS Code + PnPJs === true</li>\n<li><a href=\"https://simonagren.github.io/part3-azurefunction/\" target=\"_blank\">Part 3 - Azure Functions V2 + VS Code + PnPJs === true</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://simonagren.github.io/part4-azurefunction/\" target=\"_blank\">Part 4 - Azure Functions V2 + VS Code + PnPJs === true</a></li>\n</ul>\n<p>Let’s deploy the Function to Azure and watch it call SharePoint!</p>\n<p>This is the second post about Azure Functions V2, with PnPJs and Visual Studio code. I decided to split this post into two. The next post will focus on using the Azure Key Vault with our JavaScript Solution. </p>\n<p>This post is about deploying our app, and while we do that we have a look at the local vs productions variables.</p>\n<h1>An Azure Function to work with</h1>\n<p>Have a look at the first post if you want to install the prerequisites and build the function from scratch:\n<a href=\"https://simonagren.github.io/azurefunction-v2-pnpjs/\" target=\"_blank\">Part 1: Azure Functions V2 + VS Code + PnPJs === true</a></p>\n<p>You could also clone it from my Github and follow the instructions (please have a look at the readme):\n<a href=\"https://github.com/simonagren/azurefuncpnpjsgetlists\" target=\"_blank\">Link to GitHub Repository</a></p>\n<h1>Deploy with VS Code and Azure Function Extensions</h1>\n<p>As I mentioned earlier there are multiple ways for us to deploy this function. In the last blogpost we utilized the VS Code extension so let’s go with that first.</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Press the <code class=\"language-text\">Deploy to Function App</code></li>\n</ol>\n<p>\n  <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/deploy-8b2629525822b6a6b07b2c1aa0da63a5-204ad.jpg\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n  \n  <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n    style=\"position: relative; display: block; ; max-width: 613px; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\"\n  >\n    <span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n      style=\"padding-bottom: 66.394779771615%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/jpeg;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n    >\n      <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        style=\"width: 100%; height: 100%; margin: 0; vertical-align: middle; position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; box-shadow: inset 0px 0px 0px 400px transparent;\"\n        alt=\"deploy azure app\"\n        title=\"\"\n        src=\"/static/deploy-8b2629525822b6a6b07b2c1aa0da63a5-204ad.jpg\"\n        srcset=\"/static/deploy-8b2629525822b6a6b07b2c1aa0da63a5-fecae.jpg 200w,\n/static/deploy-8b2629525822b6a6b07b2c1aa0da63a5-ef493.jpg 400w,\n/static/deploy-8b2629525822b6a6b07b2c1aa0da63a5-204ad.jpg 613w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 613px) 100vw, 613px\"\n      />\n    </span>\n  </span>\n  \n  </a>\n    </p>\n<ol start=\"2\">\n<li>Select or create a new Function App</li>\n<li>Select or create a new Resource Group</li>\n<li>Select or create a new Storage Account</li>\n</ol>\n<p>Let the extension run its magic. After some time you should receive a message that the function has been deployed.\nRight now we don’t have any production variables, so we will use an awesome feature in the extension for this. We could also change the settings from the UI in the VS Code extension. Really smooth!</p>\n<p>\n  <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/settings-445adab8cd4140989bfc0870e03ef948-a7845.jpg\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n  \n  <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n    style=\"position: relative; display: block; ; max-width: 315px; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\"\n  >\n    <span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n      style=\"padding-bottom: 68.88888888888889%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/jpeg;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n    >\n      <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        style=\"width: 100%; height: 100%; margin: 0; vertical-align: middle; position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; box-shadow: inset 0px 0px 0px 400px transparent;\"\n        alt=\"settings\"\n        title=\"\"\n        src=\"/static/settings-445adab8cd4140989bfc0870e03ef948-a7845.jpg\"\n        srcset=\"/static/settings-445adab8cd4140989bfc0870e03ef948-368b4.jpg 200w,\n/static/settings-445adab8cd4140989bfc0870e03ef948-a7845.jpg 315w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 315px) 100vw, 315px\"\n      />\n    </span>\n  </span>\n  \n  </a>\n    </p>\n<p>It should now work in Azure, awesome!</p>\n<p>\n  <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/appsettings-22702125a72fef46dda1d7ddcc402350-57d66.jpg\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n  \n  <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n    style=\"position: relative; display: block; ; max-width: 596px; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\"\n  >\n    <span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n      style=\"padding-bottom: 103.52348993288591%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/jpeg;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n    >\n      <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        style=\"width: 100%; height: 100%; margin: 0; vertical-align: middle; position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; box-shadow: inset 0px 0px 0px 400px transparent;\"\n        alt=\"app settings\"\n        title=\"\"\n        src=\"/static/appsettings-22702125a72fef46dda1d7ddcc402350-57d66.jpg\"\n        srcset=\"/static/appsettings-22702125a72fef46dda1d7ddcc402350-18b31.jpg 200w,\n/static/appsettings-22702125a72fef46dda1d7ddcc402350-17d19.jpg 400w,\n/static/appsettings-22702125a72fef46dda1d7ddcc402350-57d66.jpg 596w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 596px) 100vw, 596px\"\n      />\n    </span>\n  </span>\n  \n  </a>\n    </p>\n<h1>Deploy via Azure Function Core Tools (CLI)</h1>\n<p>We have a couple of options, here are two:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Create a Function App via the CLI and then publish our app</li>\n<li>Create a Function App from the UI.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Just to demonstrate how to fetch the Application settings from an existing Function App, we will create a Function App from the UI.</p>\n<p>The <code class=\"language-text\">local.settings.json</code> is only being used locally, our settings are never transferred to Azure.</p>\n<h2>Create Function App from the Azure Portal</h2>\n<p>If you don’t have a function app from the previous steps, create one here.</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Log in to the Azure Portal -> Create new resource -> search for Function App and select <code class=\"language-text\">create</code>.\n\n  <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/newapp-aa58c4903c4990ddbb6fa8b7f93ebf04-44901.jpg\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n  \n  <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n    style=\"position: relative; display: block; ; max-width: 404px; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\"\n  >\n    <span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n      style=\"padding-bottom: 214.60396039603958%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/jpeg;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n    >\n      <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        style=\"width: 100%; height: 100%; margin: 0; vertical-align: middle; position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; box-shadow: inset 0px 0px 0px 400px transparent;\"\n        alt=\"new app\"\n        title=\"\"\n        src=\"/static/newapp-aa58c4903c4990ddbb6fa8b7f93ebf04-44901.jpg\"\n        srcset=\"/static/newapp-aa58c4903c4990ddbb6fa8b7f93ebf04-44dae.jpg 200w,\n/static/newapp-aa58c4903c4990ddbb6fa8b7f93ebf04-e9c43.jpg 400w,\n/static/newapp-aa58c4903c4990ddbb6fa8b7f93ebf04-44901.jpg 404w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 404px) 100vw, 404px\"\n      />\n    </span>\n  </span>\n  \n  </a>\n    </li>\n<li>Fill in all the values and then <code class=\"language-text\">create</code></li>\n<li>Wait until the app has been created</li>\n</ol>\n<h2>(OPTIONAL) Get Application Settings</h2>\n<p>We are going to use the <code class=\"language-text\">Azure Functions Core Tools</code> that we installed in the previous post, to get the application settings of our newly created app.\nWe don’t need to get these before we deploy, I’m just showing you that you can. There might be some scenarios where you would want the storage settings etc.</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Open a node console and cd into our VS Code project.</li>\n<li>\n<p>Run the following command to fetch all application settings and they will be pushed into the local.settings.json file. </p>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"javascript\">\n      <pre class=\"language-javascript\"><code class=\"language-javascript\">func azure functionapp fetch<span class=\"token operator\">-</span>app<span class=\"token operator\">-</span>settings <span class=\"token operator\">&lt;</span>FuncApp<span class=\"token operator\">></span></code></pre>\n      </div>\n</li>\n</ol>\n<h2>Deploy our function with local settings</h2>\n<p>So we publish our app and use the <code class=\"language-text\">local.settings.json</code> to overwrite the App Settings in Azure. We don’t overwrite and remove all the settings, we just add the new settings and overwrite/update if there are any with the same name.  </p>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"javascript\">\n      <pre class=\"language-javascript\"><code class=\"language-javascript\">func azure functionapp publish <span class=\"token operator\">&lt;</span>FuncApp<span class=\"token operator\">></span> <span class=\"token operator\">--</span>publish<span class=\"token operator\">-</span>local<span class=\"token operator\">-</span>settings <span class=\"token operator\">-</span>i <span class=\"token operator\">--</span>overwrite<span class=\"token operator\">-</span>settings <span class=\"token operator\">-</span>y</code></pre>\n      </div>\n<p>\n  <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/clideploy-778710f2c979314d4b57248c1bee27e1-4aa88.jpg\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n  \n  <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n    style=\"position: relative; display: block; ; max-width: 800px; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\"\n  >\n    <span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n      style=\"padding-bottom: 33.29938900203666%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/jpeg;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n    >\n      <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        style=\"width: 100%; height: 100%; margin: 0; vertical-align: middle; position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; box-shadow: inset 0px 0px 0px 400px transparent;\"\n        alt=\"cli publish\"\n        title=\"\"\n        src=\"/static/clideploy-778710f2c979314d4b57248c1bee27e1-78f2b.jpg\"\n        srcset=\"/static/clideploy-778710f2c979314d4b57248c1bee27e1-dce19.jpg 200w,\n/static/clideploy-778710f2c979314d4b57248c1bee27e1-c1413.jpg 400w,\n/static/clideploy-778710f2c979314d4b57248c1bee27e1-78f2b.jpg 800w,\n/static/clideploy-778710f2c979314d4b57248c1bee27e1-4aa88.jpg 982w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px\"\n      />\n    </span>\n  </span>\n  \n  </a>\n    </p>\n<p>And let’s try it in the browser:\n\n  <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/azuretest-cfcf889e48f012e62301033d7a46d9dd-882d2.jpg\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n  \n  <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n    style=\"position: relative; display: block; ; max-width: 757px; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\"\n  >\n    <span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n      style=\"padding-bottom: 32.23249669749009%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/jpeg;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n    >\n      <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        style=\"width: 100%; height: 100%; margin: 0; vertical-align: middle; position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; box-shadow: inset 0px 0px 0px 400px transparent;\"\n        alt=\"azure test\"\n        title=\"\"\n        src=\"/static/azuretest-cfcf889e48f012e62301033d7a46d9dd-882d2.jpg\"\n        srcset=\"/static/azuretest-cfcf889e48f012e62301033d7a46d9dd-224f9.jpg 200w,\n/static/azuretest-cfcf889e48f012e62301033d7a46d9dd-a50a6.jpg 400w,\n/static/azuretest-cfcf889e48f012e62301033d7a46d9dd-882d2.jpg 757w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 757px) 100vw, 757px\"\n      />\n    </span>\n  </span>\n  \n  </a>\n    </p>\n<h1>Recap</h1>\n<p>So deploying an Azure Function from Visual Studio Code is very easy, I like the Functions Extension. And I really like that we could change the Application Settings easily from the extension.</p>\n<p>As you saw in the other example, we created a new Function App to receive the settings from Azure. You don’t have to do that, you could fetch settings from any of your Function Apps.</p>\n<p>Another really easy way to deploy this function would be to:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Create a Function App in the Azure Portal</li>\n<li>Clone my repository from GitHub</li>\n<li>Fill in the values in local.setting.json</li>\n<li>Run <code class=\"language-text\">func azure functionapp publish &lt;FuncApp&gt; --publish-local-settings -i --overwrite-settings -y</code></li>\n</ol>\n<p>And of course, we could both get the settings, and set from local settings via the Extension in VS Code.</p>\n<p>\n  <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/local-58e4c26ddc6d592de87d028aae22db4d-710f9.jpg\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n  \n  <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n    style=\"position: relative; display: block; ; max-width: 416px; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\"\n  >\n    <span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n      style=\"padding-bottom: 63.46153846153847%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/jpeg;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n    >\n      <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        style=\"width: 100%; height: 100%; margin: 0; vertical-align: middle; position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; box-shadow: inset 0px 0px 0px 400px transparent;\"\n        alt=\"local\"\n        title=\"\"\n        src=\"/static/local-58e4c26ddc6d592de87d028aae22db4d-710f9.jpg\"\n        srcset=\"/static/local-58e4c26ddc6d592de87d028aae22db4d-cc172.jpg 200w,\n/static/local-58e4c26ddc6d592de87d028aae22db4d-f7989.jpg 400w,\n/static/local-58e4c26ddc6d592de87d028aae22db4d-710f9.jpg 416w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 416px) 100vw, 416px\"\n      />\n    </span>\n  </span>\n  \n  </a>\n    </p>\n<p>And you would be done!</p>\n<p>Anyways the next post will be using the Azure CLI and Azure Key Vault!</p>","fields":{"slug":"/part2-azurefunction/","prefix":"2018-11-18"},"frontmatter":{"title":"Part 2 - Azure Functions V2 + VS Code + PnPJs === true","author":"Simon Ågren","category":null,"tags":["sharepoint","pnp","azurefunctions","nodejs"],"cover":{"childImageSharp":{"resize":{"src":"/static/funcpnp2-55add6717461e76d8487682f8791bdf0-160fa.png"}}}}},"authornote":{"id":"/home/travis/build/simonagren/simonagren.github.io/content/parts/author.md absPath of file >>> MarkdownRemark","html":"<p><strong>Simon Ågren</strong> Passionate about SharePoint and Office365. Solution Architect working as a consultant for Sogeti in Umeå, Sweden.</p>"},"site":{"siteMetadata":{"facebook":{"appId":"2263145610597628"}}}},"pathContext":{"slug":"/part2-azurefunction/","prev":{"id":"/home/travis/build/simonagren/simonagren.github.io/content/posts/2018-11-11--azurefunction-v2-pnpjs/index.md absPath of file >>> MarkdownRemark","fields":{"slug":"/azurefunction-v2-pnpjs/","prefix":"2018-11-11"},"frontmatter":{"title":"Part 1 - Azure Functions V2 + VS Code + PnPJs === true","category":null,"tags":["sharepoint","pnp","azurefunctions","nodejs"]}},"next":{"id":"/home/travis/build/simonagren/simonagren.github.io/content/posts/2018-11-20--part3-azurefunction/index.md absPath of file >>> MarkdownRemark","fields":{"slug":"/part3-azurefunction/","prefix":"2018-11-20"},"frontmatter":{"title":"Part 3 - Azure Functions V2 + VS Code + PnPJs === true","category":null,"tags":["sharepoint","pnp","azurefunctions","nodejs"]}}}}


